The '''Space Launch System''' ('''SLS''') is an American [[Two-stage-to-orbit|two-stage]] [[Super heavy-lift launch vehicle|super heavy-lift]] [[Expendable launch system|expendable launch vehicle]] used by [[NASA]]. The primary launch vehicle for the [[Artemis program]], SLS is designed to launch the four-person [[Orion (spacecraft)|Orion spacecraft]] for missions to the Moon, on a [[trans-lunar injection]] trajectory. The rocket first launched in November 2022, carrying the uncrewed [[Artemis&nbsp;I]] mission. Its first crewed launch was for the [[Artemis&nbsp;II]] lunar [[Flyby (spaceflight)|flyby]] in April 2026, becoming the second launch vehicle to carry humans beyond [[low Earth orbit|low Earth orbit (LEO)]], after NASA's [[Saturn V]] of the [[Apollo program]].

Development of SLS began in 2011 as a congressionally mandated replacement for the retiring [[Space Shuttle]] program and the cancelled [[Ares&nbsp;I]] and [[Ares&nbsp;V]] launch vehicles of the [[Constellation program]],<!--<ref name="senatebill" /><ref name="SFN20110331" /><ref name="SR-20131125" /> --> incorporating some hardware from both programs. Costing US$31.6 billion as of 2025, the project has been criticized for mismanagement, budget overruns, and delays, but ultimately succeeded in human spaceflight in 2026.<!--<ref name="PL-111-267" /> -->

All SLS launches take place from [[Kennedy Space Center Launch Complex 39B|Launch Complex 39B]] at the [[Kennedy Space Center]] in Florida. The new [[Boeing]]-built [[Space Launch System core stage|core stage]] is powered by four ex-Shuttle [[RS-25]] engines. [[Booster (rocketry)|Attached to the core]] are two [[Northrop Grumman]] [[Space Shuttle Solid Rocket Booster#Five-segment booster|five-segment Solid Rocket Boosters]], built for the Ares vehicles, tested on [[Ares I-X]], developed from the Shuttle's [[Space Shuttle Solid Rocket Booster|four-segment SRB]]. SLS currently uses the [[Delta Cryogenic Second Stage#Interim Cryogenic Propulsion Stage|Interim Cryogenic Propulsion Stage]] (ICPS) as its second stage, for the [[Orbit insertion|insertions]] to low Earth orbit and trans-lunar injection. ICPS uses the [[RL10]] engine, and was derived from the [[Delta Cryogenic Second Stage]] designed by [[National Space Development Agency of Japan|Japan's space agency]]. [[Aerojet Rocketdyne]] builds the RS-25 and RL-10 engines.

Starting from [[Artemis V|Artemis&nbsp;V]], no earlier than late 2028, SLS will use the [[Centaur V]] upper stage, developed for the [[Vulcan Centaur]], instead of ICPS. NASA previously planned to upgrade SLS from its current Block 1 configuration to a Block 1B and Block 2, but cancelled these plans in February 2026, aiming to standardize on Block&nbsp;1, to "reduce risk and maintain schedule stability". Block&nbsp;1B was to use the [[Exploration Upper Stage]], and Block&nbsp;2 would have used new solid rocket boosters.

While SLS has the highest liftoff thrust of any rocket to ever carry humans, {{Convert|39|MN|lk=on|abbr=off}},{{Efn|The Soviet [[N-1 rocket]] produced 45.7 MN and was also designed to carry humans to the Moon, but was never flown manned. [[SpaceX Starship]] is also planned to carry humans, and has demonstrated liftoff thrust exceeding 70 MN.{{citation needed|date=April 2026}}}}<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sauers |first=Elisha |date=2026-01-17 |title=Is SLS still the most powerful rocket? 5 facts as Artemis 2 rolls out |url=https://mashable.com/article/nasa-sls-artemis-2-rollout-facts |access-date=2026-04-15 |website=Mashable |language=en}}</ref> SLS's payload capacity to [[trans-lunar injection]] of {{Convert|27|MT|lb|0}} is only around half that of the Saturn V's {{Convert|48.6|MT|lb|0}} payload.<ref name="NASA-SLS">{{cite web |title=Space Launch System (SLS) Fact Sheet |url=https://www.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/sls-4960-sls-fact-sheet-oct2024-508.pdf |publisher=NASA |access-date=2026-04-07}}</ref><ref name="NASA-SLS-secondary">{{cite web |title=SLS Space Launch System Secondary Payloads |url=https://www.nasa.gov/reference/sls-space-launch-system-secondary-payloads/ |publisher=NASA |access-date=2026-04-07}}</ref><ref name="NASA-SaturnV">{{cite report |title=Heavy-Lift Launch Vehicle Capability |url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/api/citations/20100021048/downloads/20100021048.pdf |publisher=NASA |access-date=2026-04-07}}</ref><ref name="a">{{Cite conference |title=Progress on Enabling Unprecedented Payloads for Space in the 21st Century |conference=2010 IEEE Aerospace Conference |last=Creech |first=Steve |date=2010-01-01 |url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/citations/20100017341}}</ref> Thus for Artemis lunar landings, beginning with [[Artemis IV]] targeted early 2028, Orion is planned to dock with the [[Human Landing System]] (HLS) in lunar orbit, separately launched on a non-SLS rocket; SpaceX's [[Starship HLS]] and [[Blue Origin]]'s [[Blue Moon (spacecraft)|Blue Moon]] are under development as HLS vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|title="Artemis mission plan"|url=https://www.nasa.gov/reference/human-landing-systems-2/}}</ref>

Beginning with Artemis V, NASA will transfer SLS operations to the [[Deep Space Transport LLC]], a [[Private spaceflight|commercial launch provider]] consortium of Boeing and Northrop Grumman.

== Components ==
{{See also|Super heavy-lift launch vehicle#Comparison|l1=Comparison of super heavy-lift launch vehicles}}

The SLS is a [[Shuttle-derived vehicle|Space Shuttle-derived launch vehicle]]. Its first stage consists of a central core stage powered by four engines, flanked by two space shuttle-derived solid rocket boosters.<ref name="NSFTrades" /><ref name="NSFDual" /><ref name="NSF20110616" /><ref name="nsf-20120223" />

NASA had planned to introduce upgraded variants of the rocket. The Block&nbsp;1B configuration was to incorporate a larger, purpose-built upper stage, while the Block&nbsp;2 configuration was to feature newly developed solid rocket boosters. On February 26, 2026, NASA announced that it would standardize the Block&nbsp;1 configuration and pursue alternative upper-stage options.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Grush |first=Loren |date=February 27, 2026 |title=NASA Overhauls Moon Mission in Effort to Cut Risks and Costs |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2026-02-27/nasa-overhauls-moon-mission-in-effort-to-cut-risks-and-costs |access-date=March 2, 2026 |work=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Wattles |first=Jackie |date=February 27, 2026 |title=NASA abruptly changes its roadmap to putting boots back on the moon |url=https://www.cnn.com/2026/02/27/science/nasa-moon-landing-artemis-schedule |access-date=March 2, 2026 |website=CNN |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=NASA Adds Mission to Artemis Lunar Program, Updates Architecture - NASA |url=https://www.nasa.gov/news-release/nasa-adds-mission-to-artemis-lunar-program-updates-architecture/ |access-date=March 2, 2026 |language=en-US}}</ref>

=== Core stage ===
{{main|Space Launch System core stage}}

[[File:Spacelaunchsystem-enginesection-jan2020.jpg|thumb|The SLS core stage rolling out of the [[Michoud Assembly Facility]]|left]]

The SLS core stage is built by [[Boeing]] at NASA's [[Michoud Assembly Facility]] in [[New Orleans]]. It measures {{Convert|65|m|sp=us}} in length and {{Convert|8.4|m|sp=us}} in diameter, matching the diameter of the [[Space Shuttle external tank]] to allow NASA to leverage Shuttle-era experience. The stage is visually similar to the Shuttle tank due to its rust-colored spray-on insulation.<ref name="SFN20110331" /><ref name="NSFAnnounce" />

The stage contains [[liquid hydrogen]] and [[liquid oxygen]] propellant tanks, the attach points for the solid rocket boosters, avionics, equipment for [[autogenous pressurization]] of the tanks, and the Main Propulsion System (MPS), an assembly of four [[RS-25]] engines with associated plumbing and hydraulic [[Gimbaled thrust|gimbal actuators]]. The first core stages reused MPS plumbing removed from the three remaining Space Shuttle orbiters following their decommissioning. The core stage, when combined with the solid rocket boosters, is capable of propelling the Orion spacecraft into a [[highly elliptical orbit]] without the upper stage firing, though the upper stage is required for trans-lunar injection.<ref name="NSFTrades" /><ref name="ArtDay" /><ref name="NASA_Fact-Sht" />

The core stage structure is primarily made of [[2219 aluminium alloy|2219 aluminum alloy]], and compared to the Space Shuttle external tank, several manufacturing improvements were incorporated.<ref name="NSF-20130218" /><ref name="NASA-20160602" /><ref name="NASA-20141115" /> Production began in 2014, but delays in manufacturing, testing, and integration postponed the readiness of the first flight article by several years. It uses ten barrel-shaped main sections, four domes, and seven rings.<ref name="SLS_CORE_FACT_SHEET"/>

The first four SLS missions will each use four of the remaining fourteen RS-25D engines left over from the Space Shuttle program. The final two engines needed were assembled from existing RS-25D spare parts.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Clark |first=Stephen |date=April 30, 2025 |title=NASA just swapped a 10-year-old Artemis II engine with one nearly twice its age |url=https://arstechnica.com/space/2025/04/nasa-just-swapped-a-10-year-old-artemis-ii-engine-with-one-nearly-twice-its-age/ |access-date=March 4, 2026 |work=[[Ars Technica]] |language=en}}</ref> [[Aerojet Rocketdyne]] refurbished these engines with modernized controllers, expanded throttle capability, and additional insulation to handle the higher thermal environment caused by proximity to the solid rocket boosters.<ref name="NASA-RS25-CS" /> Later flights will transition to the RS-25E, optimized for expendable use, being faster to build and costing 30% less.<ref name="NSFStennis012015" /><ref name="rocket20210329" /> Thrust for the refurbished RS-25D engines has been increased from {{cvt|2188 to 2281|kN|lb-f|lk=on|order=flip}}, while the RS-25E is rated at {{cvt|2321|kN|lb-f|order=flip}} per engine.<ref name="nsf-20201231" /><ref name="ntrs-2017" />  The first test firing of an RS-25E occurred in June 2025 and was declared successful.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Dean |first=LaToya |date=June 23, 2025 |title=NASA Tests New RS-25 Engine |url=https://www.nasa.gov/image-article/new-rs-25-engine/ |access-date=June 28, 2025 |website=NASA |language=en-US}}</ref>

The SLS uses a conical [[frustum]]-shaped [[Adapter (rocketry)|interstage]] known as the Launch Vehicle Stage Adapter (LVSA) between the core stage and the narrower diameter upper stage. The LVSA consists of sixteen [[aluminum-lithium]] panels made of [[2195 aluminium alloy|2195 aluminum alloy]] and is built by [[Teledyne Technologies|Teledyne Brown Engineering]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.tbe.com/en-us/news-and-media/Pages/teledyne-to-build-nasa-60-million-launch-vehicle-stage-adapter.aspx | title=Teledyne to Build NASA's $60 Million Launch Vehicle Stage Adapter | access-date=April 1, 2023 | archive-date=April 1, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230401232054/https://www.tbe.com/en-us/news-and-media/Pages/teledyne-to-build-nasa-60-million-launch-vehicle-stage-adapter.aspx | url-status=live}}</ref> The first unit cost approximately $60 million, with the next two costing $85 million combined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teledyne.com/en-us/news/Pages/Teledyne-Brown-Engineering-Awarded-$85-Million-NASA-Contract-to-Provide-Key-Stage-of-NASA%27s-Space-Launch-System-Vehicle-Ret.aspx|title=Teledyne Brown Engineering Awarded $85 Million NASA Contract to Provide Key Stage of NASA's Space Launch System Vehicle Returning Astronauts to the Moon|website=www.teledyne.com|access-date=May 31, 2023|archive-date=April 1, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230401232059/https://www.teledyne.com/en-us/news/Pages/Teledyne-Brown-Engineering-Awarded-%2485-Million-NASA-Contract-to-Provide-Key-Stage-of-NASA%27s-Space-Launch-System-Vehicle-Ret.aspx|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Solid rocket boosters ===
====Shuttle-derived====
[[File:Artemis II Preflight (NHQ202603300013).jpg|thumb|upright|SLS of [[Artemis&nbsp;II]], with side view showing one of the two boosters]]
The first eight SLS flights are planned to use two [[Space Shuttle Solid Rocket Booster#Five-segment booster|five-segment]] solid rocket boosters derived from the four-segment [[Space Shuttle Solid Rocket Booster]] manufactured by [[Northrop Grumman]]. The booster for the SLS incorporates casing segments previously flown as part of the Shuttle program, with the addition of a center segment to increase performance. The boosters feature updated avionics and lighter insulation but do not include a parachute recovery system, as they are expended after launch.<ref name="SFI-20160110" />

The boosters are filled with an [[ammonium perchlorate composite propellant]], consisting of [[Aluminium powder|aluminum powder]] (fuel) and [[ammonium perchlorate]] (oxidizer), bound together with [[polybutadiene acrylonitrile]]. The mixture has a rubber eraser-like consistency and is cast into each segment.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Perry |first1=Beverly |title=We've Got (Rocket) Chemistry, Part 2 |url=https://blogs.nasa.gov/Rocketology/2016/04/21/weve-got-rocket-chemistry-part-2/ |website=Rocketology: NASA's Space Launch System |publisher=National Aeronautics and Space Administration |access-date=September 30, 2022 |date=April 21, 2016 |archive-date=September 30, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220930181736/https://blogs.nasa.gov/Rocketology/2016/04/21/weve-got-rocket-chemistry-part-2/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>

At liftoff, the two boosters together produce more than 75 percent of the total thrust required to propel SLS. The five-segment configuration provides approximately 25 percent greater total impulse than the Shuttle-era boosters.<ref name="NTRS-20120507" /><ref name="NSFHowToLaunch022012" />

The available inventory of Shuttle-era booster casing segments limits use of this configuration to eight SLS flights.<ref name="NSFBoosters" />

====BOLE====
[[File:NASA, Northrop Grumman Test Fire SLS BOLE Booster (C0180 00 01 41 23 Still002 Edit).jpg|thumb|Test fire of BOLE prototype, June{{Spaces}}2025]]
The Booster Obsolescence and Life Extension (BOLE) program was announced in 2019 to develop replacement solid rocket boosters for SLS once the supply of Shuttle-derived hardware is exhausted. In 2021, NASA awarded Northrop Grumman a $3.2 billion contract to produce Shuttle-derived boosters for five missions (Artemis&nbsp;IV–VIII) and to design, develop, and test the new BOLE booster.<ref name=":4">{{Cite web |last=Clark |first=Stephen |date=June 26, 2025 |title=NASA tested a new SLS booster that may never fly, and the end of it blew off |url=https://arstechnica.com/space/2025/06/nasa-tested-a-new-sls-booster-that-may-never-fly-and-the-end-of-it-blew-off/ |access-date=June 28, 2025 |website=Ars Technica |language=en}}</ref>

The BOLE design replaces Shuttle-era steel motor cases with [[carbon-fiber composite]] cases, which are lighter and stronger. It also substitutes the hydraulic thrust vector control system with an electronic system and uses a different propellant formulation derived from Northrop Grumman's commercial solid rocket motors.<ref name=":4" />

Each BOLE booster is designed to produce approximately {{Convert|3.9|e6lb-f|MN|abbr=unit}} of thrust,<ref name=":4" /> about 19&nbsp;percent greater than the five-segment Shuttle-derived boosters, thereby increasing overall payload capability.<ref name="NSF-20210712" /><ref name="BOLEProgram" /><ref name="BOLEProgram2020" />

{{As of|2025|post=,}} BOLE remains in development. A prototype was test-fired in June 2025 but experienced a nozzle failure approximately 15 seconds before the end of the motor firing. However, the long-term future of the program is uncertain: SLS was authorized for only five flights at that time, and no funding has been provided for production of operational BOLE boosters.<ref name=":4" />

=== Upper stage ===
====Interim Cryogenic Propulsion Stage====
{{anchor|upper-stage-block-1}}
[[File:Interim Cryogenic Propulsion Stage.jpg|thumb|The [[Artemis&nbsp;I]] ICPS under construction]]

The [[Interim Cryogenic Propulsion Stage]] (ICPS) is the upper stage used on the initial Block&nbsp;1 configuration of the SLS. Three ICPS units were built by [[United Launch Alliance]] (ULA), a joint venture of Boeing and [[Lockheed Martin]]. The ICPS is derived from the [[Delta Cryogenic Second Stage]] (DCSS), incorporating minimal modifications for integration with SLS. Following the discontinuation of the DCSS, further ICPS production is no longer available as an option.

The ICPS flown on Artemis&nbsp;I was powered by a single [[RL10]]B-2 engine, also built by Aerojet Rocketdyne. The ICPS units flown on Artemis&nbsp;II and planned for use on Artemis&nbsp;IV use a single RL10C-2.<ref name="askins-20205000944" /><ref>Rosenberg, Zach. [http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/delta-second-stage-chosen-as-sls-interim-371581/ "Delta second stage chosen as SLS interim"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120727084044/http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/delta-second-stage-chosen-as-sls-interim-371581/ |date=July 27, 2012}}. ''Flight International'', May 8, 2012.</ref><ref name="NASA-20141030" />

====Exploration Upper Stage (cancelled)====
The [[Exploration Upper Stage]] (EUS) was originally planned to debut on [[Artemis&nbsp;IV]] as the upper stage for the Block&nbsp;1B configuration.<ref name="NSFPDR032015" /> It would have shared the {{Convert|8.4|m|sp=us|adj=on}} diameter of the SLS core stage and be powered by four RL10C-3 engines,<ref name="NSFEUS" /> with a later upgrade to improved RL10C-X engines.<ref name="NSF-20210304" /> Although the EUS progressed through [[Design review (U.S. government)|design review]], it did not enter full-scale hardware production and was ultimately canceled in February 2026, prior to flight.<ref name="Berger 2026">{{cite web |last=Berger |first=Eric |date=February 27, 2026 |title=NASA shakes up its Artemis program to speed up lunar return |url=https://arstechnica.com/staff/2026/02/nasa-shakes-up-its-artemis-program-to-speed-up-lunar-return/ |access-date=February 2, 2026 |work=Ars Technica}}</ref>

==== Centaur V (future) ====
In February 2026, NASA announced plans to standardize the SLS on the Block&nbsp;1 configuration and discontinue development of the EUS. With production of the DCSS ended, NASA selected an existing commercially developed upper stage for missions following depletion of the ICPS stock: ULA's [[Centaur V]], which uses a pair of RL10 engines and is expected to provide modestly improved performance over the ICPS.<ref name="Berger 2026" /><ref name=":6">{{Cite web |last=Boyer |first=Charles |date=March 6, 2026 |title=NASA Formally Selects ULA's Centaur V For Artemis IV and V |url=https://talkoftitusville.com/2026/03/06/nasa-formally-selects-ulas-centaur-v-for-artemis-iv-and-v/ |access-date=March 24, 2026 |website=TalkOfTitusville.com |language=en}}</ref>

